T1  - Can foreign firms bond themselves effectively by renting U.S. securities laws?
AU  - Siegel, Jordan
JO  - Journal of Financial Economics
VL  - 75
IS  - 2
SP  - 319
EP  - 359
PY  - 2005
DA  - 2005/02/01/
SN  - 0304-405X
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1016/j.jfineco.2004.02.001
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0304405X04001473
KW  - Law and finance
KW  - Corporate governance
KW  - Cross-listings
KW  - Reputation
KW  - Bonding
AB  - The study tests the functional convergence hypothesis, which states that foreign firms can leapfrog their countries’ weak legal institutions by listing equities in New York and agreeing to follow U.S. securities law. Evidence shows that the SEC and minority shareholders have not effectively enforced the law against cross-listed foreign firms. Detailed evidence from Mexico further shows that while some insiders exploited this weak legal enforcement with impunity, others that issued a cross-listing and passed through an economic downturn with a clean reputation went on to receive privileged long-term access to outside finance. As compared with legal bonding, reputational bonding better explains the success of cross-listings.
